+## `toRegExp(pattern: string, options?: GlobToRegExpOptions) => RegExp`
+
+Convert a glob pattern into a JavaScript `RegExp` using the same
+pattern parsing rules as `glob`.
+
+By default, the returned regular expression matches the entire
+relative path string the same way `glob` does. Set
+`fullMatch:false` to remove the leading and trailing anchors when
+you want to search for matching path fragments inside larger
+strings.
+
+```js
+const re = glob.toRegExp('src/**/*.{js,ts}')
+const jsOrTs = paths.filter(path => re.test(path))
+```
+
+```bash
+sed -n 's/^PATH=//p' manifest.txt \
+  | node -e "import { glob } from 'glob';
+const re = glob.toRegExp('src/**/*.ts')
+process.stdin.setEncoding('utf8')
+let data = ''
+process.stdin.on('data', chunk => (data += chunk))
+process.stdin.on('end', () => {
+  for (const line of data.split(/\r?\n/)) {
+    if (re.test(line)) console.log(line)
+  }
+})"
+```
+
+## `escapeRegExp(str: string) => string`
+
+Escape all regular expression syntax characters in a literal
+string. Unlike `escape()`, this does not treat glob syntax
+specially.
+
